[1] Outbreak DRC [Maniema province]
Date: Sun 7 Nov 2021
Source: Morning Express [edited]
https://morningexpress.in/eastern-drc-outbreak-of-measles-cases-in-kasongo-45-dead-in-1-month/


Some 45 people, mostly children, have died from measles in 4 weeks among more than 300 cases in Kasongo, an area of Maniema province in eastern Democratic Republic of the Congo, administrative authorities reported on Sunday [7 Nov 2021].

The health division has counted 342 cases including 45 deaths already from the 22nd to the 39th epidemiological week. "The number of victims starts at the end of September [2021]," Anadolu Benoit Kitenge, administrator of the Kasongo territory, told the Agency.

The most affected health area is the locality of Bikenge, where 3 deaths are reported on average per day, according to the same source.

In addition to measles, the territory has recorded in recent weeks, "14 cases of polio, 2 cases of yellow fever, and hundreds of deaths due to severe and rebellious malaria with anemia," says its administrator, reporting a health emergency that requires a "rapid and appropriate response."

Measles is virtually the most contagious disease in the world. It is spread by coughing, sneezing, or by direct contact with nasal or laryngeal secretions.

Children who contract the disease can face serious complications, including measles "erasing" their immune memory, putting their health and lives at risk for years, according to the World Health Organization (WHO).

In the DRC, the low vaccination rate is one of the factors explaining the resurgence of the disease. Between 2018 and 2020, the country experienced the largest outbreak on record. In just 2 years, more than 460 000 children had contracted the disease, and nearly 8000 had died from it, according to the authorities. About 3/4 of them were under 5 years old.

[Byline: Pascal Mulegwa]

